<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-082-192  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 082 192.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Transactions on Computers  Feb 1989 v38 n2 p195(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>On the complexity of single fault set diagnosability and diagnosisproblems. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Somani, Arun K.; Agarwal, Vinod K.; Avis, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Single-fault (sf) set diagnosability constitutes a generaltheoretical environment for the determination of faulty processorsin a multiprocessor system wherein each processor can be tested byneighboring processors for fault or non-fault conditions.andP;  Thesf-diagnosability problem determines if there are algorithms thatcan determine if a fault set is diagnosable.andP;  The sf-diagnosis setdetermines the exact fault set based on given syndromes.andP;  Thecomplexity of sf-diagnosability is proven to be co-non-polynomial(NP)-complete under an asymmetric invalidation model, but apolynomial-complete algorithm is developed for sf-diagnosabilityfor the symmetric invalidation model.andP;  The complexity ofsf-diagnosis is shown to be co-NP-complete for both the symmetricand asymmetric invalidation model.andP;  Development of the underlyingtheorems and proofs is described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Theoretical ResearchValidationDiagnostic AssessmentParallel AlgorithmsComputational ComplexityTechnologyFailure AnalysisParallel ProcessingProblem Solving.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Test outcomes under different models. (chart)Graph G and derived digraph D for theorem 1. (chart)An edge labeling compatible with two fault sets. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>